{{Infobox person | honorific_prefix = | name = Helen Sophia O'Hara | honorific_suffix = | image = Photo of Helen Sophia O'Hara.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1846 | birth_place = [[Portstewart]], [[County Londonderry]], [[Ireland]] | death_date = 1920 (aged 73/74) | death_place = [[County Waterford]], Ireland | resting_place = | residence = | nationality = Northern Irish | citizenship = | known_for = botanical and landscape painting | notable_works = | parents = | relatives = | signature = }}
'''Helen Sophia O'Hara''' (1846 - 1920) was a [[Northern Ireland|Northern Irish]] watercolour artist.<ref name=Butler>{{cite book|last1=Butler|first1=Patricia|title=Irish Botanical Illustrators & Flower Painters|date=2000|publisher=Antique Collectors' Club|location=Suffolk|isbn=9781851493579|page=74}}</ref>
==Life== Helen Sophia O'Hara was born in The Castle [[Portstewart]], [[County Londonderry]], in 1846. She was the daughter of the Reverend James D. O'Hara. Her brother, H.S. O'Hara was the Bishop of Cashel and Emly, and [[Lismore, County Waterford]].<ref name=Butler /> She lived with her friend and fellow artist [[Fanny Currey]] at the Mall, Lismore, from 1898 until 1919. It is believed that O'Hara received no formal training and was self-taught.<ref name=MacNally>{{cite web|last1=MacNally|first1=Niamh|title=A Subtle Art|url=http://archive.irishartsreview.com/irisartsrevi2002/pdf/2004/25503087.pdf.bannered.pdf|website=Irish Arts Review|accessdate=23 July 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724031252/http://archive.irishartsreview.com/irisartsrevi2002/pdf/2004/25503087.pdf.bannered.pdf|archivedate=24 July 2015|df=}}</ref> She died in Waterford in 1920.<ref name=Butler />
==Artistic work== [[File:'DANCING CHILDREN' BY HELEN O'HARA RUA.jpg|left|thumb|Dancing Children by O'Hara]] O'Hara was a watercolour painter, whose work centred on landscapes and seascapes, as well as flower painting. She exhibited with the [[Royal Hibernian Academy]] from 1881 to 1894. She was a member of the [[Royal Ulster Academy|Belfast Art Society]] (BAS), and although she retired in 1895, she was elected vice-president in 1896. Whilst living in Lismore with Currey, O'Hara illustrated a number of Currey's children's books. Her work was exhibited with the [[Society of Women Artists]], the [[Dudley Museum and Art Gallery|Dudley Gallery]], and the [[Royal Institute of Painters in Water Colours]].<ref name=Butler /> She exhibited over 100 artworks, landscapes and seascapes, with the [[Water Colour Society of Ireland]] from 1892 to 1913.<ref name=MacNally /> O'Hara was elected an honorary member of the BAS in 1904 along with [[Mildred Anne Butler]], [[John Lavery]], and [[Frank Spenlove-Spenlove]]. The [[Ulster Museum]] holds a number of her works.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Butler|first1=Patricia A.|title=Three Hundred Years of Irish Watercolours and Drawings|date=1997|publisher=Phoenix Illustrated|location=London|isbn=0753802066|page=157}}</ref>
