{{About|the book by William Bennett|the Chinese classic text|Tao Te Ching}}
{{Italic title}}

'''''The Book of Virtues: A Treasury of Great Moral Stories''''', sometimes shortened to '''''The Book of Virtues''''' ({{ISBN|0-684-83577-0}}), is an anthology edited by [[William Bennett]]. It was published on November 1, 1993 by [[Simon & Schuster]] and was followed by ''The Moral Compass: Stories for a Life's Journey'', in late 1995.

The book is intended for the moral education of the young and is divided into different virtues: [[self-discipline]], [[compassion]], [[moral responsibility|responsibility]], [[friendship]], [[employment|work]], [[courage]], [[wikt:perseverance|perseverance]], [[honesty]], [[loyalty]], and [[faith]].

A spinoff for young audiences called ''The Children's Book of Virtues'' also came out in 1995. A year later, it served as the basis for a [[PBS Kids]] [[Adventures from the Book of Virtues|TV series]].

Bennett had served as [[Secretary of Education]] for President [[Ronald Reagan]] and often made school trips during his tenure. According to Bennett, the ''Book of Virtues'' grew out of conversations with teachers, who expressed difficulty in communicating common moral principles to diverse student bodies.<ref>http://conversationswithbillkristol.org/video/bill-bennett/</ref>

